316. parsi: elsewhere with an infin„ but here in combination with sedulo it has almost the meaning of dare operam and can take a ne-clause. '

317. sarta tecta, in good repair, a technical term used of houses. The figure is continued in 323, and is the subject of an elaborate canti- cum in lllost. I. 2 (85 ff). Cf. Cic. Fam. XIII. 50, M’. Curium ‘sar- tum et tectum,' ut aiunt, con-sertas.

318. tibi, mihi: Introd. 15 α.

320. paenitet, is dissatisfied, is not content. This is the only meaning of paenitere in Pl„ never, to be sorry sor. The line means that he only is really good who is not content with his attainments in goodness, but desires to be better. — frugi bonae : Capt. 956 n.

322. contemnit: i.e., the state of mind expressed in paenitet. — industria, good purpose ,· cf. ex industris, intentionally.

324. ob eam rem: antecedent of quia, here emphatic in order to correct the father’s insinuation that he was boasting (318).

326. huic : the general principle that laic refers to the speaker is extended so as to make it a proper pronoun to use of any person or thing in the speaker’s presence; in particular, it is used of persons whose house is represented on the stage, as in this case. So 212, 214, 359, and often. Other pronouns may of course be used of the same persons, illum 114, illi 133.

327. caute et cogitate : see Introd. 12.
